The paper proposes a probabilistic framework based on deep generative models for missing value imputation, which involves the use of deep neural networks (DNNs) to capture nonlinear relationships between missing entries and observed values. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and databases (cs.DB). Additionally, the paper's use of DNNs and probabilistic modeling aligns with the sub-categories of neural networks (cs.NE) and computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CV).
